# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1903-boston-americans-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1901-boston-americans-season] The **1901 Boston Americans season** was the first season for the professional baseball franchise that later became known as the Boston Red Sox, and the first season of play for the American League (AL).
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1901-boston-americans-season] It resulted in the Americans finishing second in the AL with a record of 79 wins and 57 losses, four games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1901-boston-americans-season] The team was managed by Jimmy Collins and played its home games at Huntington Avenue Grounds.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1901-boston-americans-season] On February 11, Jimmy Collins, third baseman for the National League Boston Beaneaters became the first player under contract for the Boston Americans after being offered a contract of $4000 with the added ability to sign subsequent players to contracts.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Collins was joined on March 4 by the outfielder Chick Stahl, who was also from the Beaneaters.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Defecting with Stahl and Collins was the outfielder Buck Freeman.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Yet perhaps the most important signing was that of the 34 year old St.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Louis Cardinals pitcher Cy Young, who accepted a contract worth $3500 from the Boston Americans.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Vital to the signing of Cy Young from the Cardinals was the signing of Cy Young's catcher in St.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Louis, Lou Criger; the value that Young gave to Criger and that Criger gave to Young was so strong, that it is unlikely that Young would have signed for the Americans if Criger had not done so.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Prior to the regular season, the team held spring training in Charlottesville, Virginia.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1901-boston-americans-season] The total attendance for the Red Sox was 289,448, the second most in the American League (behind the White Sox' 354,350) and more than the crosstown Boston Beaneaters' 146,502.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1901-boston-americans-season] The offense was led by Buck Freeman, who hit 12 home runs and had 114 RBIs while recording a .339 batting average.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1901-boston-americans-season] The pitching staff was led by Cy Young, who made 43 appearances (41 starts) and pitched 38 complete games with a 33–10 record and 1.62 ERA, while striking out 158 in 371+1⁄3 innings.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1901-boston-americans-season] The team had two games end in a tie; August 31 at Detroit Tigers and September 12 at Washington Senators.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Tied games are not counted in league standings, but player statistics during tied games are counted.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1901-boston-americans-season] Cy Young led the league in ERA (1.62), shutouts (5; tied with Clark Griffith), strikeouts (158), and wins (33).
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1901 Chicago White Stockings season** was their first season as a major league team, and their second season in Chicago.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] It was also the inaugural season of American League as a major league.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings had a very balanced lineup, which was led by outfielders Dummy Hoy and Fielder Jones, and scored the most runs in the AL.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] They relied primarily on speed, as Frank Isbell, Sam Mertes, and Jones finished 1–2–3 in stolen bases.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The pitching staff was anchored by Clark Griffith, who went 24–7 with a 2.67 ERA.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The **1901 major league baseball season** was contested from April 18 through October 6, 1901.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] It was the inaugural major league season for the American League (AL) (having previously been the minor league Western League), with the Chicago White Stockings winning the AL pennant.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] In the National League (NL), in operation since 1876, the Pittsburgh Pirates won the NL pennant.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first season of the modern era.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This would be the only season in which the Milwaukee Brewers played, as the team would relocate to St.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Louis, Missouri for the following season as the St.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns (before that team relocated to Baltimore, Maryland as the modern Baltimore Orioles in 1954, where they remain to this day.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The Baltimore Orioles of this season would fold following the 1902 season).
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The 1901 schedule consisted of 140 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 20 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This format had previously been used by the National League during their 1888–1891 seasons.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This format would last until 1904, which saw an increase of games played.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on April 18 with a game between the Brooklyn Superbas and the Philadelphia Phillies, while American League Opening Day did not take place until April 24, with a game between the Chicago White Stockings and the Cleveland Bluebirds.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The American League would see its final day of the season on September 28, while the National League would see its final day of the season on October 6.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] On February 27, 1901, the National League Rules Committee announced several rule changes, effective immediately.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Blue laws restricted Sunday activities in several localities, causing several teams to play at ballparks in a different locality.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] 15 tie games (8 in AL, 7 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Reds would play their final game at League Park, on October 6 during a doubleheader against the St.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals, moving into the Palace of the Fans for the start of the 1902 season.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1902-boston-americans-season] The **1902 Boston Americans season** was the second season for the professional baseball franchise that later became known as the Boston Red Sox.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1902-boston-americans-season] The Americans finished third in the American League (AL) with a record of 77 wins and 60 losses, 6+1⁄2 games behind the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1902-boston-americans-season] The Americans bolstered their pitching by recruiting Bill Dinneen, who jumped from the Boston Beaneaters.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1902-boston-americans-season] Dinneen and Cy Young would become the "one-two" pitching combination for the Boston Americans.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1902-boston-americans-season] Prior to the regular season, the team held spring training in Augusta, Georgia.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1902-boston-americans-season] The offense was led by Buck Freeman, who hit 11 home runs and had 121 RBIs, and Patsy Dougherty with a .342 batting average.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1902-boston-americans-season] The pitching staff was led by Cy Young, who made 45 appearances (43 starts) and pitched 41 complete games with a 32–11 record and 2.15 ERA, while striking out 160 in 384+2⁄3 innings.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1902-boston-americans-season] The team had one game end in a tie; August 18 vs.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1902-boston-americans-season] Tie games are not counted in league standings, but player statistics during tie games are counted.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The **1902 Philadelphia Athletics season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The team finished first in the American League with a record of 83 wins and 53 losses.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] In 1902, the Philadelphia Phillies obtained an injunction, effective only in Pennsylvania, barring Athletics' second baseman Nap Lajoie from playing baseball for any team other than the Phillies.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] Lajoie had played for the Athletics in 1901, and appeared in just one game in 1902 before the injunction went into effect.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The American League responded by transferring Lajoie's contract to the Cleveland Bronchos, who were subsequently known as the "Naps" in Lajoie's honor for several seasons.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] Following the A's pennant winning season, the *Philadelphia Inquirer* organized a championship parade for the team through the city on Monday night, September 30, 1902.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The team proceeded in open carriages and were reviewed by Philadelphia Mayor Ashbridge in front of the *Inquirer'*s building on Market Street.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] "There were more than 25,000 base ball enthusiasts from Philadelphia and nearly every town within a radius of twenty miles of the city in the parade.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] A thousand effigies of the "white elephant" were carried by the paraders.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] There were fifteen bands and twenty fife and drum corps in line to furnish music for the marchers." It was estimated that more than 200,000 turned out for the parade.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The **1903 Boston Americans season** was the third season for the professional baseball franchise that later became known as the Boston Red Sox.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Americans finished first in the American League (AL) with a record of 91 wins and 47 losses, 14+1⁄2 games ahead of the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Boston went on to participate in the first World Series held between the AL and National League (NL) champions.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Americans won the 1903 World Series in eight games over the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Prior to the regular season, the team held spring training in Macon, Georgia.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Cy Young was a coach for the Mercer University baseball team, also based in Macon.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Boston Americans played an exhibition game against Mercer University (with Cy Young pitching for Mercer) on March 23; the outcome being a 13─2 victory for Boston.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team's longest losing streak was three games, which occurred twice; April 20–23 and September 22–23.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team's longest game was 12 innings, which occurred three times.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The offense was led by Buck Freeman, who hit 13 home runs and had 104 RBIs, and Patsy Dougherty with a .331 batting average.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1903-boston-americans-season] It was Freeman's third consecutive season with at least 100 RBIs.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The pitching staff was led by Cy Young, who made 40 appearances (35 starts) and pitched 34 complete games with a 28–9 record and 2.08 ERA, while striking out 176 in 341+2⁄3 innings.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team had two other 20-game winners; Bill Dinneen (21–13) and Tom Hughes (20–7).
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team had three games end in a tie; July 31 at Washington, August 29 at Washington, and September 25 vs.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Boston had an 11-game winning streak from May 28 through June 8, to put themselves in the AL lead.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1903-boston-americans-season] While they briefly fell into second place in mid-June, behind Philadelphia, Boston then won 9-of-10 to recapture the lead, which they held through the end of the season.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Americans met the Pittsburgh Pirates in the first modern World Series, an agreement between the AL and the NL as a post-season tournament.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The "Amerks" won the best-of-nine series in eight games; after falling behind, 3–1, they won four games in a row, clinching the championship at their home field, the Huntington Avenue Grounds, in Boston.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1903-boston-beaneaters-season] The **1903 Boston Beaneaters season** was the 33rd season of the franchise.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1903-boston-beaneaters-season] The team finished sixth in the National League with a record of 58–80, 32 games behind the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1903-brooklyn-superbas-season] The **1903 Brooklyn Superbas season** was a season in Major League Baseball.
[src:1903-boston-americans-season/1903-brooklyn-superbas-season] The Superbas began their slide from contention in the National League by finishing in fifth place.
